Virtual Machines are widely used to host applications in the cloud, especially when full control over the operating system is required.

For example, a company can deploy a backend API on a Linux VM and configure custom dependencies, runtime environments, and security settings.

A real-life use case is hosting enterprise applications such as ERP systems that require specific OS configurations.

Another example is running game servers on VMs, where developers need full control over performance tuning and networking.

VMs are also used for hosting databases, middleware, and legacy applications that cannot be easily migrated to platform services.

This makes VMs a versatile solution for application hosting in cloud environments.
